57.1:
Maysti&rtail; Geraud ne telleth no forther of the conquest; bot of þe lette where-throgh the lond was not clenlych I-conquered, ne the folk fully I-broght yn thedone, he telleth such resons:—Thay that fyrst come&ntail;, hadde&ntail; ful wel I-spedde wyth-out any lette, yif þe kynge ne hadd so astyly
 I-sent, & forboden that no man ne shold to ham come; & thay that we&rtail; ynto þe lond I-come, shold the lond leue, & turne ayeyne, othe&rtail; forlese al that thay helden of the kynge yn othe&rtail; londes.  And wha&ntail; the kynge was ynto the lond hymself I-come wyth so moch power, hyt had he wel ynoght, na&rtail; that he hadd so sone turned ayeyne, throgh the popes heste & þe cardynals, & eke the lyddernesse that hys sones hadden I-purueyed to do hym, the whyll that he was out of lond.  ffor the folk that, at the begynnynge of so sodeyne comynge, was so swyth amayed, & aferd & agrysed of the wepned men stalwarthnesse, and of the derne wondynge of arwes, throgh lange abydynge & sleuyth of Maystres that no stalwarthnesse ne sykernesse was wyth, by lytyll & lytel lerned, wepne to ber&rtail;, arwes to shote; & so wel woned ham ther-to, that oft ham byfelle wonderly goode happes yn fyght vpo&ntail; englysshe-me&ntail;; & on thys maner, that at the begynnynge lyghly myght be I-shent & I-broght vnder fote, worthe&ntail; bold & staluarth to wythstond, & defend ham-self.  Me may rede & ouerseche the boke of kynges, þe prophetes, al the old rede fro end to othe&rtail;, & other tymes that afoor haue I-be; me shal neuer fynd that wer&rtail; & hate came vpo&ntail; folk, bot for ha&rtail; synnes; & so hyt may wel be of the folk of Irland, that oft serued wel, for ha&rtail; synnes, to haue werre & wrak of othe&rtail; out-londes men; natheles, god almyghty was nat ham so wengeable wrot, that he tholled ham fully, nether al to be vndone, ne fully I-broght yn-to theudome, nether thay clenly forelore grace; ne the other clenlych hadden grace, the Maystrye to hawe, ham fully & preysebly yn theudome for to hold.  Me fynt that þe Iresshemen hadde&ntail; four prophetes, euery yn hys tyme, Patryk, Molynge, Braken, & Colmkylly, whos bokes ben wyth ham an Iresshe I-wrytte; euery of ham speke&ntail; of the fyght of thys conqueste, & seyne that 'lange stryf & oft fyghtynge shal be for thys lond; & oft the lond shal be I-horyed & I-steyned wyth grete slaght of men.'  Bot vnnethe thay beheteth the Englyssh peple fully þe maystrye a lytell a&rtail; domesday, & that the lond shal from see to see be I-castelled & fully I-won.  Bot the englysshe-me&ntail; sholle&ntail;, ar that, oft wel feble be, & myche desayse yn the lond so ? se .  Barca&ntail;
 seyth, that 'throg&hbar; a kynge that shal come out of the wyl montayngnes of seynt patrykes þat me cleppeth slesto (slesco ?), & on a soneday-nyght , a castel yn the wodd contreys of Offalye shal to-brek, most what al the Englysshe-men of Irland shullen be I-stourbet' //
